{{Politics of the United States}}
The '''president pro tempore of the United States Senate''' (often shortened to '''president pro tem''') is the second-highest-ranking official of the [[United States Senate]]. [[Article One of the United States Constitution|Article One]], Section Three of the [[United States Constitution]] provides that the [[Vice President of the United States|vice president of the United States]] is the [[Presiding Officer of the United States Senate|president of the Senate]] (despite not being a senator), and mandates that the Senate must choose a president ''[[pro tempore]]'' to act in the vice president's absence. Unlike the vice president, the president pro tempore is an elected member of the Senate, able to speak or vote on any issue. Selected by the Senate at large, the president pro tempore has enjoyed many privileges and some limited powers.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/protempresidents00wash/page/9|title=Pro Tem: Presidents Pro Tempore of the United States Senate since 1789|author1=Senate Historical Office|author2=With a preface by Senator [[Robert C. Byrd]], President pro tempore|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|editor1-last=Erickson|editor1-first=Nancy (Secretary of the Senate)|page=[https://archive.org/details/protempresidents00wash/page/9 9]|isbn=978-0-16-079984-6|date=2008|access-date=January 9, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; During the vice president's absence, the president pro tempore is empowered to preside over Senate sessions. In practice, neither the vice president nor the president pro tempore usually presides; instead, the duty of presiding officer is rotated among junior U.S. senators of the majority party to give them experience in [[parliamentary procedure]].&lt;ref name=&quot;cnn&quot;&gt;{{cite web |title=Hillary takes Senate gavel–for an hour |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/ALLPOLITICS/stories/01/24/hillary.senate/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100120220245/http://archives.cnn.com/2001/ALLPOLITICS/stories/01/24/hillary.senate/index.html |archive-date=January 20, 2010 |publisher=CNN |date=January 24, 2001}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Since 1890, the most [[Seniority in the United States Senate|senior U.S. senator]] in the majority party has generally been chosen to be president pro tempore and holds the office continuously until the election of another. This tradition has been observed without interruption since 1949.&lt;ref name=Davis2012&gt;{{cite report |last=Davis |first=Christopher M. |title=The President Pro Tempore of the Senate: History and Authority of the Office |url=https://www.senate.gov/CRSReports/crs-publish.cfm?pid=%270E%2C%2APL%3F%3D%22P%20%20%0A |date=December 20, 2012 |publisher=Congressional Research Service |accessdate=February 23, 2015 |ref=harv}}&lt;/ref&gt; Since the enactment of the current [[Presidential Succession Act]] in 1947, the president pro tempore is third in the [[United States presidential line of succession|line of succession to the presidency]], after the vice president and the [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|speaker of the House of Representatives]] and ahead of the [[United States Secretary of State|secretary of state]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| title=A president resigns, dies or is impeached: What is the line of succession?| website=wftv.com| last=Lord| first=Debbie| url=https://www.wftv.com/news/trending-now/a-president-resigns-dies-or-is-impeached-what-is-the-line-of-succession/772080208| publisher=Cox Media Group| date=June 18, 2018| accessdate=June 18, 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The current president pro tempore of the Senate is [[Iowa]] [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Chuck Grassley]]. Elected on January 3, 2019, he is the 91st person to serve in this office.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=Grassley Sworn in as Senate President Pro Tempore |url=https://www.grassley.senate.gov/news/news-releases/grassley-sworn-senate-president-pro-tempore |date=January 3, 2018 |publisher=Chuck Grassley: United States Senator for Iowa |access-date=January 4, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Power and responsibilities==

Although the position is in some ways analogous to the [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|speaker of the House of Representatives]], the powers of the president pro tempore are far more limited. In the Senate, most power rests with party leaders and individual senators, but as the [[Presiding Officer of the United States Senate|chamber's presiding officer]], the president pro tempore is authorized to perform certain duties in the absence of the vice president, including ruling on [[point of order|points of order]].&lt;ref name=&quot;SenPPT&quot;&gt;{{cite web |title=President Pro Tempore |url=https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/common/briefing/President_Pro_Tempore.htm |website=United States Senate |accessdate=May 2, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; Additionally, under the [[Twenty-fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|25th Amendment to the Constitution]], the president pro tempore and the speaker are the two authorities to whom declarations must be transmitted that the president is unable to perform the duties of the office, or is able to resume doing so. The president pro tempore is third in the line of [[United States presidential line of succession|presidential succession]], following the vice president and the speaker,&lt;ref name=&quot;SenPPT&quot; /&gt; and consequently is one of the few members of Congress entitled to a full-time [[U.S. Capitol Police|security detail]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |last=Stricherz |first=Mark |title=Congressional Security Details Remain Murky |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/policy/those-who-protect-members-of-congress-remain-out-of-the-spotlight |website=rollcall.com |date=June 16, 2017 |accessdate=March 18, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt; Additional duties include appointment of various congressional officers, certain commissions, advisory boards, and committees and joint supervision of the congressional [[United States Senate Page#School|page school]].&lt;ref name=&quot;SenPPT&quot; /&gt; The president pro tempore is the designated legal recipient of various reports to the Senate, including [[War Powers Resolution|War Powers Act]] reports under which he or she, jointly with the speaker, may have the president call Congress back into session. The officeholder is an [[ex officio member|''ex officio'' member]] of various boards and commissions. With the [[Secretary of the Senate|secretary]] and [[Sergeant at Arms of the Senate|sergeant at arms]], the president pro tempore maintains order in Senate portions of the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]] and Senate buildings.&lt;ref name=&quot;SenPPT&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;HAO&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |last=Sachs |first=Richard C. |title=The President Pro Tempore of the Senate: History and Authority of the Office |journal=Congressional Research Service Report|publisher=[[Congressional Research Service]] |date=January 22, 2003 |url=https://www.senate.gov/CRSReports/crs-publish.cfm?pid=%270E%2C*PL%3F%3D%22P%20%20%0A |format=PDF |accessdate=December 9, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==History==
===Position established===
The office of president pro tempore was established by the [[Constitution of the United States]] in 1789. Between 1792 and 1886, the president pro tempore was second in the line of [[United States presidential line of succession|presidential succession]], following the vice president and preceding the speaker. Through 1891, the president pro tempore was appointed on an intermittent basis only, when the vice president was not present to preside over the Senate, or at the adjournment of a session of Congress.&lt;ref name=&quot;gp&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreenpapers.com/Hx/CongressionalLeadership.html|title=A Brief History of Congressional Leadership|author=Richard E. Berg-Andersson|date=June 7, 2001|work=The Green Papers|accessdate=November 17, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; 

The first president pro tempore, [[John Langdon (politician)|John Langdon]], was elected on April 6, 1789,&lt;ref name=&quot;SenPPT&quot;/&gt; serving four separate terms between 1789 and 1793. More than twelve senators{{clarify|date=January 2020}} held the office during the Senate's first decade,&lt;ref name=&quot;Protem–1&quot;&gt;{{cite book| title=Pro tem : presidents pro tempore of the United States Senate since 1789| editor-last=Erickson| editor-first=Nancy| publisher=U.S. Government Printing office| location=Washington, D.C.| date=August 22, 2008| isbn=978-0-16-079984-6| pages=[https://archive.org/details/protempresidents00wash/page/7 7–10]| chapter=Chapter 1:The Formative Years, 1789–1860| chapterurl=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/GPO-CPUB-110spub18/pdf/GPO-CPUB-110spub18-1-6.pdf| accessdate=July 12, 2018| url=https://archive.org/details/protempresidents00wash/page/7}}&lt;/ref&gt; presiding over sessions, signing legislation, and performing routine administrative tasks.

Whenever the office of the vice presidency was vacant, as it was on ten occasions between 1812 and 1889,&lt;ref name=CRSsuccession22&gt;{{cite web| last=Neale| first=Thomas H.| title=Presidential and Vice Presidential Succession: Overview and Current Legislation|page=22| work=CRS Report for Congress| url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/RL31761.pdf| publisher=[[Congressional Research Service]], the [[Library of Congress]]| location=Washington, D.C.| date=September 27, 2004| accessdate=June 16, 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt; the office garnered heightened importance, for although he did not assume the vice presidency, the president pro tempore stood next in line for the presidency.&lt;ref name=JT10th&gt;{{cite web| title=John Tyler, Tenth Vice President (1841)| url=https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/common/generic/VP_John_Tyler.htm| publisher= Office of the Secretary, United States Senate| location=Washington, D.C.| accessdate=June 30, 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt; Before the ratification of the Twenty-fifth Amendment in 1967, a vacancy in the vice presidency could be filled only by a regular election; several individuals who served during these vacancies were referred to informally as &quot;acting vice president.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| title=Lafayette Foster| url=https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/art/artifact/Sculpture_21_00006.htm| work=Art &amp; History| publisher=Secretary of the Senate| location=Washington, D.C.| accessdate=July 12, 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;

On three occasions during the 19th century, the Senate was without both a president and a president pro tempore:

*from July 9 to July 11, 1850, following [[Millard Fillmore]]'s accession to the presidency upon the death of [[Zachary Taylor]], until [[William R. King]] was elected president pro tempore;&lt;ref name=65FFH104105&gt;{{cite book| title=From Failing Hands: the Story of Presidential Succession| last1=Feerick| first1=John D.| last2=Freund| first2=Paul A.| date=1965| url=https://ir.lawnet.fordham.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1000&amp;context=twentyfifth_amendment_books| publisher=Fordham University Press| location=New York City| pages=104–105| lccn=65-14917}}&lt;/ref&gt;
*from September 19 to October 10, 1881, following [[Chester Arthur]]'s accession to the presidency upon the death of [[James A. Garfield]], until [[Thomas F. Bayard]] was elected president pro tempore;&lt;ref name=&quot;Protem–2&quot;&gt;{{cite book| title=Pro tem : presidents pro tempore of the United States Senate since 1789| editor-last=Erickson| editor-first=Nancy| publisher=U.S. Government Printing office| location=Washington, D.C.| date=August 22, 2008| isbn=978-0-16-079984-6| pages=[https://archive.org/details/protempresidents00wash/page/55 55–57]| chapter=Chapter 2: A Question of Succession, 1861-1889| chapterurl=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/GPO-CPUB-110spub18/pdf/GPO-CPUB-110spub18-1-7.pdf| accessdate=July 12, 2018| url=https://archive.org/details/protempresidents00wash/page/55}}&lt;/ref&gt;
*from November 25 to December 7, 1885, following the death of Vice President [[Thomas A. Hendricks]], until [[John Sherman (politician)|John Sherman]] was elected president pro tempore.&lt;ref name=&quot;Protem–2&quot;/&gt;

When President [[Andrew Johnson]], who had no vice president, was [[Impeachment of Andrew Johnson|impeached and tried]] in 1868, Senate President pro tempore [[Benjamin Wade|Benjamin Franklin Wade]] was next in line to the presidency. Wade's radicalism is thought by many historians to be a major reason why the Senate, which did not want to see Wade in the [[White House]], acquitted Johnson.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Gene|title=High Crimes and Misdemeanors: The Impeachment and Trial of Andrew Johnson|publisher=William Morrow &amp; Company|year=1977|isbn=0-688-03072-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/highcrimesmisdem00smit}}&lt;/ref&gt; The president pro tempore and the speaker of the House were removed from the [[United States presidential line of succession|presidential line of succession]] in 1886. Both were restored to it in 1947, though this time with the president pro tempore following the speaker.&lt;ref name=&quot;SenPPT&quot;/&gt;

[[William P. Frye]] served as president pro tempore from 1896 to 1911 (the [[Fifty-fourth United States Congress|54th]] through the [[Sixty-second United States Congress|62nd Congress]]), a tenure longer than anyone else. He resigned from the position due to ill health shortly before his death. Electing his successor proved difficult, as Senate Republicans, then in the majority, were split between [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] and [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] factions, each promoting its own candidate. Likewise, the Democrats proposed their own candidate. As a result of this three-way split, no individual received a majority vote. It took four months for a compromise solution to emerge: Democrat [[Augustus Octavius Bacon|Augustus Bacon]] served for a single day, August 14, 1911, during the vice president's absence. Thereafter, Bacon and four Republicans—[[Charles Curtis]], [[Jacob Harold Gallinger|Jacob Gallinger]], [[Henry Cabot Lodge]], and [[Frank B. Brandegee|Frank Brandegee]]—alternated as president pro tempore for the remainder of the Congress.&lt;ref name=&quot;SenPPT&quot;/&gt;

===Modern era===
[[File:WHOportTyler.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.80|[[John Tyler]] is the only Senate president pro tempore to also become [[President of the United States]].]]
In January 1945, the [[79th United States Congress|79th Congress]] elected [[Kenneth McKellar (politician)|Kenneth McKellar]], who at the time was the [[Dean of the United States Senate|senator with the longest continuous service]], to be president pro tempore. Since then, it has become customary for the majority party's senior member to hold this position. [[Arthur H. Vandenberg|Arthur Vandenberg]] (from 1947 to 1949) was the last president pro tempore not to be the senior member of the majority party, aside from the single day in December 1980 accorded [[Milton Young]], who was the retiring senior member of the Republican Party, which would hold the majority in the incoming [[97th United States Congress|97th Congress]].&lt;ref name=Davis2012/&gt;

Three presidents pro tempore have gone on to be elected to the office of vice president—[[John Tyler]], [[William R. King]], and [[Charles Curtis]]—of whom Tyler is the only one to become president, assuming the office in April 1841 upon the death of [[William Henry Harrison]].

==Related officials==
